description: After a rain

Based on what appears to be an ovipositor, I believe this is a female cricket who has lost her back right leg. I believe this is either Gryllus veletis or Gryllus pennsylvanicus, but as they so closely resembles each other as to thwart easy differentiation (Montana Field Guide, n.d.-a & -b), I have been unable to narrow my observation to the species level. They both belong to Family Gryllidae, however (Montana Field Guide, n.d.-b).

Although I heard a possibly separate cricket individual of unknown species a few minutes earlier in a different area, this one made no sound. As this is Juneâ€”after the termination of G. veletisâ€™ song and prior to its death, as well as prior to the onset of G. pennsylvanicusâ€™ mating song (Montana Field Guide, n.d.-b) (assuming they behave similarly in CO as in MT, and that the aforementioned singing cricket belonged to a third species)â€”its silence does not help me very much. (Especially as I presumably would have been perceived as a potential predator).

Montana Field Guide. (n.d.-a). Spring field cricket-Gryllus veletis. Montana Natural Heritage Program. Retrieved June 27, 2022, from https://fieldguide.mt.gov/speciesDetail.aspx?elcode=IIORT69020.

Montana Field Guide. (n.d.-b). Fall field cricket - Gryllus pennsylvanicus. Montana Natural Heritage Program. Retrieved June 27, 2022, from https://fieldguide.mt.gov/speciesDetail.aspx?elcode=IIORT69010."
